Syntax vs.Semantics

Syntax: The set of rules governing the formation of expressions in a programming language.

Semantics: The meaning of those expressions.

There are several forms of language semantics: * Axiomatic semantics: A set of axiomatic truths in a programming language. * Denotational semantics: Modeling a program as a collection of set-theoretic functions with specific properties. * Operational semantics: A mathematical model of the execution of a program.

Operational Semantics

Operational semantics: For a programming language, the mathematical definition of a set-theoretic relation \(e \Rightarrow v\), where \(v\) is the value produced when the program \(e\) is executed.

Structural operational semantics (small-step semantics: A formal proof of how the individual steps in a computation take place in program execution.

Natural Semantics: Formal proof of how the overall results of executions are obtained.

Linking back to the practical

Interpreters and compilers have to address both the syntax and semantics of programs * They first must determine if the syntax of a program is correct * Must verify that the program is well-formed for this language * And produce a representation that can be used to verify the semantics * Then they must verify that the semantics is correct: the program produces the correct result

There are a set of concepts from discrete math and computational theory that will be the foundation of our interpreters.

The Basics

Strings, symbols, and alphabets

  • Strings of characters are one of fundamental data structures of computing

An alphabet is any nonempty finite set. The elements of an alphabet are the symbols of the alphabet.

A string over an alphabet is a finite sequence of symbols from that alphabet

A language is a set of strings.

Alphabets, Strings, and Languages

Given an alphabet \(\Sigma\), define \(\Sigma^{*}\) to be set of all strings on that alphabet and \(\Sigma^{+}\) to be the set of all strings on that alphabet excluding the empty string. A language \(L \subseteq \Sigma\) is some subset of strings in the alphabet \(\Sigma\). A string in \(L\) is sometimes called a sentence.

Regular Expressions

Formal Definition of Regular Expressions

Primitive Regular Expression A Primitive regular expression defined over some finite alphabet \(\Sigma\) is defined as one of the following:

Empty set

\(\emptyset\) which denotes the empty set,

Empty string

\(\epsilon\) which denotes the set containing only the empty string, which has no characters,

Literal character

Some \(a \in \Sigma\) denoting the set containing only the character \(a\)

Formal Definition of Regular Expressions

  • We build larger regular expressions by defining three operations:

    Concatenation

    \(RS\) is the set of strings that can be obtained by concatenating a string from \(R\) with a string from \(S\)

    Alternation

    \(R|S\) denotes the set union of sets described by \(R\) and \(S\)

    Kleene star

    \(R^{*}\) denotes the smallest superset of the set described by \(R\) that contains \(\epsilon\) and is closed under concatenation.

Regular Grammars

Who Remembers How To Diagram A Sentence?

A language has a grammar

  • A grammar for the English language tells us whether or not a sentence is well-formed.

  • For example:

    • <sentence> \(\rightarrow\) <noun-phrase>``<predicate>

    • <noun-phrase> \(\rightarrow\) <article>``<noun>

    • <predicate> \(\rightarrow\) <verb>

A grammar \(G\) is defined as a quadruple \(G=(V,T,S,P)\) where:

  • \(V\) is a finite set of objects called variables

  • \(T\) is a finite set of objects called terminal symbols

  • \(S \in V\) is a special symbol called the start symbol

  • \(P\) is a finite set of productions

A production is a rule of the form \(x \rightarrow y\) where \(x \in (V \cup T)^{+}\) and \(y \in (V \cup T)^{*}\)

We say that \(w \Rightarrow z\) is a derivation of \(z\) from \(w\) by applying some production from \(G\) to the string \(w\) to generate \(z\)

For a grammar \(G\), then the set \(L(G) = \{w \in T^{*}: S \dot{\Rightarrow} w\}\) is the language generated by G and \(\dot{\Rightarrow}\) indicates some number of derivations applied to a variable or terminal resulted in some variable or terminal.

Let \(\Sigma = \{a,b\}\) and \(n_{a}(w)\) and \(n_{b}(w)\) be the number of \(a\) and \(b\) symobls in a string \(w\). Then the grammar \(G\) with productions $$ \[\begin{aligned} \label{eq:gramex1} S &\rightarrow SS\nonumber\\ S &\rightarrow \epsilon\nonumber\\ S &\rightarrow aSb\nonumber\\ S &\rightarrow bSa\nonumber \end{aligned}\]

$$ will generate the language \(L=\{w:n_{a}(w)=n_{b}(w)\}\)

This claim isnt obvious on an initial read of the example. Consider that every sentence generated by the grammar will have equal numbers of \(a\) and \(b\) symbols as every production that generate an \(a\) simultaneously dervies a string with an \(a\) and \(b\). But what about cases where a string might begin and end with the same symbol?

Proof. Proceed by induction, Assume that all \(w\in L\) with length \(|w|\leq 2n\) can be derived with \(G\). Take any \(w\in L\) of length \(2n+2\). If \(w=aw_{1}b\), then \(w_{1} \in L\) and \(|w_{1}=2n\).

By the induction assumption, then \(S \dot{\Rightarrow} w_{1}\). This means that \[S \Rightarrow aSb \dot{\Rightarrow} a_{w_{1}}b = w\] and that \(w\) can be derived from \(G\). A similar argument applies for \(w=bw_{1}a\).

If \(w\) begins and ends with the same symbol, then we can apply a counting argument with \(+1\) and \(-1\) to show that it has form \(w=w_{1}w_{2}\) with a \(w_{1} \in L\) and \(w_{2} in L\) and \(|w_{1}|\leq 2n\) and \(|w_{2} \leq 2n\). Hence, \[S \Rightarrow SS \dot{\Rightarrow} w_{1}S \dot{\rightarrow} w_{1}w_{2}=w\]

This shows that the inductive argument holds for the case \(n=1\) and we have a basis for claiming this to be true for \(n\)

Consider the grammar \(G=(\{A,S\},\{a,b\},S,P_{1})\) where \(P_{1}\) consists of the productions: $$ \[\begin{aligned} S &\rightarrow aAb | \epsilon\nonumber\\ A &\rightarrow aAb | \epsilon\nonumber \end{aligned}\]

$$

The language generated by this grammar is \(L(G)=\{a^{n}b^{n}:n\geq 0\}\)

A grammar \(G=(V,T,S,P)\) is right-linear if all productions are of the form: $$ \[\begin{aligned} A \rightarrow xB\nonumber\\ A \rightarrow x\nonumber \end{aligned}\]

$$ where \(A,B \in V\) and \(x \in T^{*}\).

A grammar \(G=(V,T,S,P)\) is left-linear if all productions are of the form: $$ \[\begin{aligned} A \rightarrow Bx\nonumber\\ A \rightarrow x\nonumber \end{aligned}\]

$$ where \(A,B \in V\) and \(x \in T^{*}\).

A regular grammar is either a left-linear or right-linear grammar.

Right linear grammars generate regular languages

Let \(G=(V,T,S,P)\) be a right-linear grammar. Then \(L(G)\) is a regular language.

What happens when we perform operations on regular languages?

Three Basic Questions

  • What happens when you perform operations on regular languages?

  • How can one determine if a regular language has certain properties?

  • How can one tell if a language is a regular language?

These questions consider the properties and behavior of regular languages. Is it possible that all languages are regular? Can any set be accepted by some, admittedly very complex, finite automaton? What properties are common to all regular languages.

Closure Properties

  • Consider the regular languages \(L_{1}\) and \(L_{2}\). Is \(L_{1} \cup L_{2}\) regular?

  • Is this true for all regular languages? If so, then we say that the family of regular languages is closed under union.

  • There are many other operations that may also be closed for the family of regular languages

Closure under set operations

The family of regular languages is closed under the operations of union, intersection, complementation, and Kleene closure.

  • This says that given regular languages \(L_{1}\) and \(L_{2}\), then \(L_{1} \cup L_{2}\), \(L_{1} \cap L_{2}\), \(\overline{L_{1}}\), and \(L_{1}^{*}\) are also regular languages

Prove that \(L_{1} \cup L_{2}\) is regular

Proof. If \(L_{1}\) and \(L_{2}\) are regular, then there are R.E. \(r_{1}\) and \(r_{2}\) that are regular expressions that match those languages. By definition, the regular expressions resulting from the union, concatenation, and Kleene-closure are regular expressions. By definition, there are matching regular languages for each of those quantities.

Prove that \(\overline{L_{1}}\) is regular

Proof. Let \(M=(Q,\Sigma,\sigma,q_{0},F)\) be a dfa that accepts \(L_{1}\). Then, the dfa \(\overline{M}=(Q,\Sigma,q_{0},Q-F)\) is a dfa that accepts \(\overline{L_{1}}\). By definition, the extended transition function \(\sigma^{*}\) is a total function (covers all input). Thus, for a string \(w\), either the result of \(\sigma^{*}(q_{0},w)\) is a final state of \(M\) and \(w \in L_{1}\) or the result is not a final state and \(w \in \overline{L_{1}}\).

Prove that \(L_{1} \cap L_{2}\) is regular

Proof. By DeMorgans Law, \(L_{1} \cap \L_{2} = \overline{\overline{L_{1}} \cup \overline{L_{2}}}\). We have just proved that regular languages are closed under both complementation and union, therefore intersection is also closed.

Note that there is an alternate constructive proof of this fact in the textbook. It proceeds from the DFAs that recognize each language and constructs a combined DFA whose states are pairs selected from states of the individual DFAs. The transition function of the combined DFA does the same. The set of final states of the combined DFA is defined as the set of pairs of states from the individual DFAs s.t. the states are final states of the respective DFA.

Other operations

  • One can prove other set operations using the results from the previous theorems

  • For example, it is clear from the definition of set difference that it is closed for the family of regular languages

  • Other operations can be proved by more primitive operations (in the same manner as the constructive proof for set intersection)

Closure under other operations

A homomorphism is a substitution in which a single letter is replaced by a string. Formally, for two alphabets \(\Sigma\) and \(\Gamma\), a homomorphism is a function \(h: \Sigma \rightarrow \Gamma^{*}\).

  • One can extend this to strings: for \(w=a_{1}a_{2}\ldots a_{n}\), then \(h(w)=h(a_{1})h(a_{2})\ldots h(a_{n})\)

  • If \(L\) is a language on \(\Sigma\), then its homomorphic image is the set \(h(L)=\{h(w): w \in L\}\).

If we have a regular expression \(r\) for a language \(L\), then a regular expression for \(h(L)\) is obtained by applying the homomorphism to each symbol in \(r\)

Let \(\Sigma = \{a,b\}\) and \(\Gamma = \{b,c,d\}\). Let \(h\) be: $$ \[\begin{aligned} h(a) &= dbcc \nonumber\\ h(b) &= bdc \nonumber \end{aligned}\]

$$

If \(L\) is the regular language denoted by \(r=(a+b^{*})(aa)^{*}\), then regular language \(h(L)\) is denoted by \(r_{h}=(dbcc + (bdc)^{*})(dbccdbcc)^{*}\).

Determining Properties of a Regular Language

Two Important Concerns

  • Membership:Given a language \(L\) and a string \(w\), can we determine if \(w \in L\)?

  • Standard representation:For that matter, what does it mean when we say Given a language \(L\)...

    • A language is in standard representation if it is described by a FA, regular expression, or grammar

The first question is known as the membership question and a method for answering it is known as a membership algorithm. Determining if such an algorithm exists and constructing an efficient instance of that algorithm is a critical problem in language theory. This is a simple task for our starter case of regular languages but not so simple for languages that we will consider in later discussions.

Weve been using multiple methods to address the second issue: verbal descriptions, set notation, finite automata, regular expressions, and regular languages. Of those, only the last three provide sufficient rigor for us to use them in reasoning about languages. So, we will say that a language is in a standard representation if it is described by a finite automata, regular expression, or regular grammar.

Given a standard representation of any regular language \(L\) on alphabet \(\Sigma\) and string \(w\in \Sigma^{*}\), there exists an algorithm for determining whether or not \(w \in L\) and whether or not \(L\) is empty, finite, or infinite

Proof. The algorithm is generated by representing the language by a DFA and testing to see if \(w\) is accepted by that DFA. We know the language is not empty if there exists a simple path through the DFAs transition graph from an initial vertex to any final vertex. The language is infinite if there is at least one cycle in the transition graph and the base vertex of any of these cycles is on the path from the initial vertex to the any final vertex.

For any two languages \(L_{1}\) and \(L_{2}\) in standard representation, there exists an algorithm to determine whether or not \(L_{1} = L_{2}\).

Proof. Let \[L_{3} = (L_{1} \cap \overline{L_{2}}) \cup (\overline{L_{1}} \cap L_{2})\] By closure, \(L_{3}\) is regular and there exists a DFA \(M\) that accepts \(L_{3}\). By the previous theorem, we can construct an algorithm that determines if \(L_{3}\) is empty. But, we know that \(L_{3}\) can only be empty if \(L_{1} = L_{2}\).

Identifying Non-regular Languages: Pumping Lemmas

Let \(B = \{0^{n}1^{n}: n \geq 0\}\). Is this language regular?

  • An attempt to construct a DFA that recognizes the language \(B\) will show that the DFA needs to remember how many \(0\) symbols have been read as processes the input stream.

  • But that number isnt limited, so the DFA will have to keep track of infinite number of possibilities, which cant be done in a finite number of states!

But dont be fooled again

Consider the following languages over the alphabet \(\Sigma = \{0,1\}\): $$ \[\begin{aligned} C &= \{w: \text{w has equal number of zeros and ones}\}\nonumber\\ D &= \{w: \text{w has equal number of 01 and 10 substrings}\}\nonumber \end{aligned}\]

$$

  • Just because a language appears to require unbounded memory to be recognized doesnt necessarily mean that is the case

  • The surprise is that the language \(C\) is not regular but \(D\) is regular!

The Pumping Lemma

If \(L\) is regular language, then there is some pumping length \(p\) where, if \(s\) is any string in \(L\) of at least length \(p\), then \(s\) can subdivided into three substrings \(s=xyz\) s.t.:

  1. \(\forall i \geq 0, xy^{i}z \in L\)

  2. \(|y| > 0\)

  3. \(|xy| \leq p\)

Why is this called a pumping lemma? The theorem says that an essential property of all regular languages is that they can be pumped: that is, for some sufficiently long word, that word will have a middle section that can be repeated an arbitrary number of times to produce a new word in same language.

Note that this lemma applies trivially to finite languages by setting the pumping length equal to the maximum string length in the language plus one.

Pigeonhole Principle

  • If \(p+1\) pigeons are placed into \(p\) holes, then, as one might expect, there will be at least one hole with more than one pigeon stuck in it.

Proof. Define \(M=(Q,\Sigma,\sigma,q_{1},F)\) be a DFA that recognizes \(L\). Furthermore, let \(|Q| = p\).

If \(s \in L\) has length at least \(p\), consider the sequence of states that \(M\) goes through when given \(s\) as input. If \(n\) is the length of string \(s\), then \(n+1\) is the length of the path we took through \(M\) recognizing \(S\). Since \(n\) is at least \(p\), then, by the pigeonhole principle, \(n+1\) must be greater than p and the path must contain at least one repeated state.

Divide \(s=xyz\) where \(x\) is the sub-string up the repeated state, \(y\) is the piece between the repeated states, and \(z\) is the remainder. These strings satisfy the conditions in the theorem (details in the textbook).

Using the pumping lemma to disprove regularity

  • Proceed by contradiction and assume that the language \(L\) is regular.

  • Use the pumping lemma to find a length \(p\) s.t. all strings in \(L\) can be pumped

  • Find a string \(s\in L\) that cannot be pumped. Consider the ways that \(s\) can be divided in sub-strings that fulfill the pumping lemma

Think of using the pumping lemma as a game

  • Let your opponent pick \(p\)

  • For that value of \(p\), choose a string \(s\) in \(L\) s.t. \(|s| \geq p\)

  • Your oppenent selects \(x\), \(y\), and \(z\) s.t. \(s=xyz\) s.t. \(|xy|\leq m, |y| \geq 1\)

  • We now try to find a number \(i\) s.t. \(w_{i}=xy^{i}z\) is not in \(L\)

The language \(L=\{(ab)^{n}a^{k}:n > k, k \geq 0\}\) is not regular.

Proof. Given \(p\), select \(s=(ab)^{p+1}a^{p}\). Because of the constraint that \(|xy|\leq p\), both \(x\) and \(y\) must be somewhere in \((ab)^{p+1}\). Your opponent picks \(y=a\) and so we select \(i=0\). Result is not in \(L((ab)^{*}a^{*})\). If our opponent pick \(y=ab\), then again choose \(i=0\) and a similiar argument applies.

Show that \(B=\{0^{n}1^{n}: n\geq 0\}\) is not regular.

Given \(p\), select \(s=0^{p}1^{p}\). So, \(s\in B\) and \(|s|>p\), then write \(s=xyz\), where for any \(i\geq 0\), \(xy^{i}z \in B\). Three cases shows this is a contradiction:

  1. The string consists only of 0s. In this case, \(xyyz\) has more 0s than 1s and so is not a member of \(B\)

  2. A similar contradiction occurs if \(y\) consists only of 1s.

  3. If \(y\) consists of both 0s and 1s, \(xyyz\) may have the same number of 0s and 1s but they will be out of order. So \(xyyz\) is not in \(B\).

Show that \(C=\{w: \text{w has equal numbers of 0s and 1s}\}\) is not regular.

Assume that \(C\) is regular and \(p\) is the pumping length for \(C\). Let \(s=0^{p}1^{p}\). We need to show that C being regular says that applying the pumping lemma means that \(s=xyz\) where for any \(i\geq 0\), \(xy^{i}z \in C\). Note that the pumping lemma says \(|xy|\leq p\). If so, then \(y\) must contain only 0s and so \(xyyz\) cannot be in \(C\).

Pitfalls using the pumping lemma

  • Note the pumping lemma must be used to show that a language is NOT regular.

  • Remember: always start with a string in the language of interest.

  • Note that we can only assume what the pumping lemma tells us about the decomposition \(xyz\)

Note that the pumping lemma cannot be used to show that a language is regular. Even if you can show that now string in a language can be pumped out, you cannot conclude that language is regular.

It is very easy to chose poorly when selecting a string. Trying to show a language where the strings have the form \(a^{n}\) where \(n\) is prime by saying Given \(p\), let \(w=a^{p}\) is incorrect as \(p\) may not be prime!

Finally, assume only the things that the pumping lemma tells you to assume and nothing more. This can be difficult at times.

More Examples of Using the Pumping Lemma

Let \(C=\{w|w \text{ has an equal number of 0's and 1's}\}\). Use the pumping lemma to prove \(C\) is not regular.

Proof. Proceed by contradiction. Assume that \(C\) is regular. Let \(p\) be the pumping length given by the pumping lemma. Let \(s=0^{p}1^{p}\). By the pumping lemma, \(s\) can be split into three pieces, \(s=xyz\) where for any \(i\geq0\), \(xy^{i}z\) is in \(C\). So, it appears that \(C\) can be pumped.

Note that the third condition on the pumping lemma stipulates that any pumping of \(s\) must ensure that \(|xy| < p\). But that implies that the string \(y\) must consist only of \(0\)s. Thus \(xyyz\) is not in \(C\). The string \(s\) cannot be pumped, which is a contradiction.

More Examples of Using the Pumping Lemma

Let \(F=\{ww | w \in \{0,1\}^{*} \}\). Use the pumping lemma to show that \(F\) is non-regular.

Proof. Proceed by contradiction by assuming that \(F\) is regular. Let \(p\) be the pumping length given by the pumping lemma and \(s = 0^{p}10^{p}1\). As \(s \in F\) and has length \(|s| > p\), we can split \(s\) into three parts \(s=xyz\). Now show that we cant satisfy the conditions of the pumping lemma using this construction.

Again, the pumping lemma tells us that any pumping of \(s\) must ensure that \(|xy| < p\). But that implies that \(y\) must consist only of \(0\)s so \(xyyz\) is not in \(F.\)

Note The Difficulty

  • The selection of the string \(s\) requires care as we need a string that cannot be pumped

  • In the first example, if we had chosen \(s=(01)^{p}\), we would not have produced a contradiction as that string can be pumped in the language \(C\)

  • A similar issue exists with a bad choice in our second example. For example, the string \(0^{p}0^{p}\) can be pumped in \(F\). You have to find something like \(0^{p}10^{p}1\) that exhibits the essence of the nonregularity of the \(F\)

A final note about the pumping lemma

The pumping lemma is one of the more difficult concepts in theory of computer science (and general mathematics) to understand. This is one of the first instances one finds in the undergradate study of math where you have to use an advisoral argument and thats a tough thing to do.

Context-Free Languages

Consider matching parenthesis

  • Note: \(L=\{a^{n}b^{n}: n\geq 0\}\) is not regular

  • Narrow the problem so that we let \(a=(\) and \(b=)\)

  • In other words, make certain we have matching parentheses

  • OK... so a very simple property of programming languages cant be represented by regular languages

A grammar \(G=(V,T,S,P)\) is context-free if all productions in \(P\) have the form \[A \rightarrow \alpha\] where \(A\in V\) and \(\alpha \in (V\cup T)^{*}\).

  • Context-free: the substitution of the variable does not depend upon the symbols in the rest of the sentential form.

Regular grammars restrict in two ways: (1) the left side must be a simple variable, and (2) the right side has restrictions on the form of the production. By definition, every regular grammar is context-free... but we have seen languages that are non-regular.

The term context-free derives from the fact that the substitution of the variable on the left of the production can be made any time such a variable appears in a sentence. That is, it does not depend on the symbols in the rest of sentential form (the context).

Applying Productions

  • The set \(P\) are pairs formatted as \(\alpha \rightarrow \beta\) where \(\alpha \in V\) is a nonterminal and \(\beta \in (V\cup\Sigma)^{*}\) is a string of variables and/or terminals

  • The r.h.s. of a production \(\beta\) can be the empty string \(\epsilon\), with \(\alpha \rightarrow \epsilon\) is called an \(\epsilon\)-production

Applying Productions

  • For strings \(u,v \in (V\cup \Sigma)^{*}\), we say \(u\) directly yields \(v\), \(u \Rightarrow v\), if \(\exists(\alpha,\beta) \in P\), s.t. \(v\) is the result of apply the production to \(u\).

  • For strings \(u,v \in (V\cup \Sigma)^{*}\), we say \(u\) yields \(v\) (or \(v\) is derived from \(u\)), if \(\exists(k > 0)\) and strings \(u_{1},\ldots,u_{k} \in (V\cup \Sigma)^{*}\) such we can apply productions that yields \(u \Rightarrow u_{1} \Rightarrow \ldots \Rightarrow u_{k} \Rightarrow v\)

Context-free Language

The language of a context-free grammar \(G=(V,\Sigma,R,S)\) is the set: \[L(G)=\{w\in \Sigma^{*}: S \overset{*}{\Rightarrow} w \}\]

Examples of Context-Free Languages

The language \(L=\{ww^{R}: w \in \{0,1\}^{*}\}\) can be derived from the context-free grammar \(G=(\{S\},\{0,1\},S,P)\) with productions: $$ \[\begin{aligned} S &\rightarrow 0S0\nonumber\\ S &\rightarrow 1S1\nonumber\\ S &\rightarrow \lambda \end{aligned}\]

$$

Examples of Context-Free Languages

Take the string \(s=011110\). The derivation of this string from the grammar \(G\) is: $$ \[\begin{aligned} S &\rightarrow 0S0\nonumber\\ &\rightarrow 01S10\nonumber\\ &\rightarrow 011S110\nonumber\\ &\rightarrow 011\lambda 110 \rightarrow 011110\nonumber\\ \end{aligned}\]

$$

Examples of Context-Free Languages

The context-free grammar \(G\) with productions: $$ \[\begin{aligned} S &\rightarrow abB\nonumber\\ A &\rightarrow abBb\nonumber\\ B &\rightarrow bbAa\nonumber\\ A &\rightarrow \lambda\nonumber\\ \end{aligned}\]

$$

  • Note that the language \(L=\{ab(bbaa)^{n}bba(ba)^{n}: n\geq 0\}\).

Try some sample derivations of strings using the grammar to see this is the case.

  2. Give three examples of strings in \(L(G)\)?

  3. Give three examples of strings not in \(L(G)\)?

  4. Can I derive \(aba\) directly from the production \(T\)?

  5. Can I derive \(aba\) from the production \(T\)?

  6. Can I derive \(T\) directly from \(T\)?

  7. Can I derive \(T\) from the production \(T\)?

Non-Linear Grammars

Non-Linear Grammars

Write a context-free grammar for \(L=\{a^{n}b^{m}: n \neq m\}\).

For \(n=m\):

$$\[\begin{aligned} S &\rightarrow aSb\nonumber\\ S &\rightarrow \lambda \end{aligned}\]

$$

For \(n>m\):

$$\[\begin{aligned} S &\rightarrow AS_{1}\nonumber\\ S_{1} &\rightarrow aS_{1}b | \lambda\nonumber\\ A &\rightarrow aA | a \end{aligned}\]

$$

For \(n<m\)

$$\[\begin{aligned} S &\rightarrow AS_{1}|S_{1}B\nonumber\\ S_{1} &\rightarrow aS_{1}b | \lambda\nonumber\\ A &\rightarrow aA | a\nonumber\\ B &\rightarrow bB | b \end{aligned}\]

$$

Non-Linear Grammars

Consider the grammar \(G\) with productions \(S\rightarrow aSb|SS|\lambda\).

The language for this grammar \(L=\{w\in \{a,b\}^{*}: n_{a}(w)= n_{b}(w) \wedge n_{a}(v)\geq n_{b}(v), \text{ \textit{v} is a prefix of \textbf{w}}\}\)

Note what happens when we replace \(a\) and \(b\) with ( and ). The language \(L\) recognizes strings such as (()) and ()()(). In other words, the entire set of properly nested parenthesis structures in most programming languages.

Leftmost and Rightmost Derivations

Consider the grammar \(G=(\{A,B,S\},\{a,b\},S,P)\) with productions: $$ \[\begin{aligned} S &\rightarrow AB\nonumber\\ A &\rightarrow aaA\nonumber\\ A &\rightarrow \lambda\nonumber\\ B &\rightarrow Bb\nonumber\\ B &\rightarrow \lambda\nonumber \end{aligned}\]

$$

Consider the derivations: $$ \[\begin{aligned} S &\Rightarrow AB \Rightarrow aaAB \Rightarrow aaB \Rightarrow aaBb \Rightarrow aab\\ S &\Rightarrow AB \Rightarrow ABb \Rightarrow aaABb \Rightarrow aaAb \Rightarrow aab \end{aligned}\]

$$

Note that both derivations use the same set of productions. The difference is only in the order in which the productions are applied. But, there are times when order is significant.

A leftmost derivation is a derivation where in each step the leftmost variable in the sentential form is replaced. The rightmost derivation is a derivation where the rightmost variable is replaced.

Derivation Trees

$$\[\begin{aligned} S &\rightarrow aAB\nonumber\\ A &\rightarrow bBb\nonumber\\ B &\rightarrow A | \lambda \end{aligned}\]

$$

  • This tree is a partial derivation tree for this grammar

  • Tree root is the start symbol

  • Ends with leaves that are terminals

Derivation Trees

  • A synonym for derivation tree is parse tree.

Let \(G=(V,T,S,P)\) be a context-free grammar (CFG). An ordered tree \(T\) is a derivation tree for \(G\) iff

  • The root of \(T\) is labeled \(S\)

  • Every leaf has a label from \(T \cup \{\lambda\}\)

  • Every interior node has a label from \(V\)

  • If a node is labeled \(A \in V\) and its children are labeled \(a_{1},a_{2},\ldots, a_{n}\), then a production \(A \rightarrow a_{1},a_{2},\ldots, a_{n}\) is in \(P\)

  • A leaf labeled \(\lambda\) has no siblings.

A partial derivation tree is a tree with a root not necessarily from \(S\) and every leaf has a label from \(V\cup T \cup \{\lambda\}\). The yield of the tree is string obtained by reading the leaves of the tree from left to right, omitting any nodes labeled \(\lambda\).

Abiguity in grammars

A grammar can be ambiguous

  • It is possible that a grammar can generate the same string in different ways

  • In this case, we say that the grammar is ambiguous in nature

Ambiguity

Now consider how the following grammar generates the string \(a+a*a\):

$$ \[\begin{aligned} EXPR &\rightarrow EXPR + EXPR \nonumber\\ EXPR &\rightarrow EXPR * EXPR \nonumber\\ EXPR &\rightarrow ( EXPR )\nonumber\\ EXPR &\rightarrow a \end{aligned}\]

$$

This grammar is attempting to codify the rules of arithmetic precedence. But the second grammar doesnt capture the usual precedence relations and may group the + or * operators in the wrong order. The issue is that grammar is ambiguous: there are multiple derivation strings

Ambiguity

Now consider how the following grammar generates the string \(a+a*a\):

$$ \[\begin{aligned} \label{eq:ambig1} EXPR &\rightarrow EXPR + TERM | TERM \nonumber\\ TERM &\rightarrow TERM * FEXPR | FEXPR \nonumber\\ FEXPR &\rightarrow ( EXPR )\nonumber\\ FEXPR &\rightarrow a \end{aligned}\]

$$

This grammar generates the same language as the previous grammar but every generated string has a unique parse tree.

Note that we have addressed the ambiguous nature of the previous example. Can you explain what aspect of mathematical expressions this grammar addresses that the previous grammar did not?
